## Background
Resolves #1309 

## Problem
Direct use of `to_i64` on `bigdecimal::BigDecimal` literals resulted in floating-point numbers like `2.0` being mistakenly interpreted as integers.

## Solution
We improved the mechanism to determine if a given `BigDecimal` is an integer or a floating-point number:

### Initial Approach:
Initially, we determined the type of number by comparing its digit count with the length of its string representation.

```rust
fn is_integer_representation(bigdecimal_val: &BigDecimal) -> bool {
    let bigdecimal_val_str = bigdecimal_val.abs().to_string();
    bigdecimal_val.abs().digits() == bigdecimal_val_str.len() as u64
}
```

### Enhanced Solution (Already Applied):
With the introduction of the [get_scale](https://github.com/akubera/bigdecimal-rs/pull/116) method, we optimized the process by directly accessing the scale of a `BigDecimal`. This method efficiently discerns between integers and numbers with fractional components.

```rust
fn is_integer_representation(bigdecimal_val: &BigDecimal) -> bool {
    bigdecimal_val.get_scale() == 0
}
```

## Code Update
The parsing approach for `Literal::Number` was adjusted based on the enhanced solution:

```rust
impl TryFrom<&Literal<'_>> for Value {
    // ... rest of the implementation ...
    fn try_from(literal: &Literal<'_>) -> Result<Self> {
        match literal {
            Literal::Number(bigdecimal_val) => {
                if is_integer_representation(bigdecimal_val) {
                    convert_to_i64(bigdecimal_val)
                } else {
                    convert_to_f64(bigdecimal_val)
                }
            },
            // ... other match arms ...
        }
    }
}
```

## Tests
Tests have been added, as referenced in the original issue, to validate the applied solution.

## Further Enhancement

In our initial refactoring efforts, we had made use of an `is_integer()` method to determine if a `BigDecimal` was an integer or not. Post our code enhancements, we have now replaced the usage of the `is_integer()` function with the more efficient `is_integer_representation()` method. 

The new method's implementation is as follows:

```rust
fn is_integer_representation(&self) -> bool {
    self.fractional_digit_count() == 0
}
```

This refined approach ensures a more direct and accurate check for integer representation, optimizing both readability and performance. We have updated all relevant parts of our codebase to reflect this change, ensuring a consistent and efficient mechanism to handle `BigDecimal` numbers.

## Conclusion

By leveraging the capabilities of the `BigDecimal` crate and our improved detection mechanism, we have enhanced the accuracy and efficiency of our number type determination process. The updates and tests ensure that our implementation correctly interprets floating-point numbers and integers, addressing the issues identified in #1309.

Add run, count, test and named_test methods to Tester instance.
Apply pretty_assertions::assert_eq.

1. run
```rust
// before
run!("SELECT * From Foo;");

// after
g.run("SELECT * FROM Foo;").await.unwrap();
```

2. test
```rust
// as-is
test! {
    sql: "SELECT * FROM Foo",
    expected: Ok(select!( .. ))
};

// to-be
g.test(
    "SELECT * FROM Foo",
    Ok(select!( .. ));
).await
```

3. migrations
migration work for existing test-suite modules are also simple.
e.g. `test-suite/src/case.rs`

```rust
// as-is
for (sql, expected) in test_cases {
    test!(sql, expected);
}

// to-be
let g = get_tester!();

for (sql, expected) in test_cases {
    g.test(sql, expected).await;
}
```

